    background: `Imee Marcos is a senator in the 19th Congress, serving her first term since 2019. She is the daughter of former dictator Ferdinand E. Marcos and Imelda Marcos, and the sister of President Ferdinand “Bongbong” Marcos Jr. Imee began her political career in 1975, serving as chair of Kabataang Barangay and later as assemblywoman for Ilocos Norte from 1984 to 1986. After her family’s exile to Hawaii, she returned to politics in 1998, serving as representative of Ilocos Norte and later as governor from 2007 to 2019. Despite claiming to have graduated from prestigious institutions like Princeton University, University of the Philippines (UP), and the Asian Institute of Management (AIM), investigations revealed that these claims were unsubstantiated. Marcos faced legal issues, including a 1991 court ruling in Hawaii that found her civilly liable for the wrongful death of student Archimedes Trajano, though the Philippine Supreme Court did not enforce the ruling. Marcos has also been involved in controversies, such as being linked to a secret offshore trust in 2013, misuse of tobacco tax funds in 2017, and being a beneficiary of illegally created Swiss foundations. She currently chairs four Senate committees, including those on cooperatives, electoral reforms, foreign relations, and social justice.`,
