    background: `Liza Largoza Maza is an activist and former congresswoman, known for her advocacy for women’s rights and social justice. She represented Bayan Muna and Gabriela Women’s Party in Congress from 2001 to 2010. A graduate in business economics from the University of the Philippines, Maza was a strong advocate for migrant workers even before her congressional tenure. She authored key laws such as the Rent Control Act, Juvenile Justice and Welfare Act, and the Anti-Trafficking in Persons Act. Maza was also Chair Emerita of GABRIELA Women’s Alliance and the International Women’s Alliance. She faced murder charges in 2006, which were dismissed in 2018, and was briefly barred from leaving the Philippines in 2015. Maza served as the head of the National Anti-Poverty Commission before resigning in 2018. She is running for the Senate in 2025 under the Makabayan Coalition.`,
